  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "XsD3zN43bt1OVl3XrrDl4ciIKBg=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:34.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "A load-bearing design rule: encryption lives at the `/bytes` layer, NOT the feed layer. Feeds store plain-text references (content hashes). The data those references point to is what is encrypted.\n\nConsequences:\n\n- Anyone can read the feed and obtain the reference, but without the wallet-derived AES key the `/bytes` payload is opaque.\n- Feed-level optimizations (like `uploadReference` vs `uploadPayload`, or batching multiple feed updates) don't affect encryption \u2014 they only change how the 64-char hash gets packed into the Single Owner Chunk (SOC), not the encrypted data at `/bytes`.\n- The same pattern works for document, drive, and user manifests: serialize JSON, encrypt, upload to `/bytes`, then write only the hash to the feed.\n\nThis separation is also why the feed SOC stays tiny (8-byte timestamp + 64-byte reference = 72 bytes) even when manifests grow large.",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:34.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:34.000Z"
    }
  },
